Another thing to note is, the reason electricity is flowing through the paper clip as you read it with the voltmeter is because the voltmeter actually completes the circuit. The paper clip being inside the outlet, just sitting there, does not have electricity flowing through it until the circuit is complete, as previously stated. However, the voltmeter being attached to the paper clip and neutral completes the circuit so it’s actually connected to both sides of the outlet. The paper clip on its own simply acts as an extension of the hot side of the outlet.

In Australia residual current detectors (RCD, also know as earth leakage detectors) are compulsory in all new installations, and are in the late stages of being phased in to older installations. As opposed to a circuit breaker, that works at a certain number of ampres (I'm guessing 20A in America?), an RCD trips at the slightest discrepancy between the hot current and the return current through the neutral. Just a few mA will trip an RCD. So if you touch a hot lead, instead of relying on the circuit breaker to save you, the RCS will detect that some current is going to earth rather than neutral, and cut the power.

In your experiment it looks like you only have a OCPD (Over Current Protection Device) that triggers. In Germany a residual current operated circuit breaker (RCCB) is mandatory in households. This would break the circuit on very low currents if it flows through your body into the ground. You would still get shocked and you should go to the hospital to get your heart checked, but the sausage burning stuff wouldn't happen to your fingers if enough current goes to the ground (and those breakers are very sensitive).

What actually happens in AC power is both poles (live and neutral) rapidly change polarity (+ and -) meaning neutral is positive for a 1/60th or 1/50th of a second and live is negative for 1/60th or 1/50th of a second and vice versa hence the name alternating current. It changes polarity 60 times a second in 60Hz regions (The Americas and some Asian countries) and 50 times a second in 50Hz regions (Europe and surrounding areas).

I never plug anything directly into a wall outlet.  I always use a 1:1 isolation transformer for everything whether it be my coffee maker, phone charger, desk lamp or power tools.  That way, the neutral is ungrounded (isolated) giving you a hot side has no voltage with respect to the ground you're on so that you will not get a shock if you accidentally touch the hot wire (you can still get a shock if you touch both wires).

Technically black is only one of the 6 main color codes for electrical wires in the US. They go in order: Black, Red, Blue, Brown, Orange, Yellow. Black red and blue are used to identify low voltage circuits (120 and below), and brown orange and yellow are used to identify high voltage (240 and up). There is also a second color to identify a neutral Grey. This is typically used for high voltage neutrals (480+). The way you determine which colors to use is by first determining your voltage and then counting your phases which go as follows: (120) phase circuit # 1,3,5; 2,4,6 black red blue; (240+) 1,3,5; 2,4,6 brown orange yellow

Improperly explained. It is not the voltage that makes the muscles contract, it's the current. That's why you can handle the connections on a 12V 500A car battery with no problems (voltage is too low to break the resistance of the skin) and touch a live 15.000 V wire as long as the current is low, like 0.01mA, like what happens when you touch a plasma ball.

Home-use Muscle stimulators (Like an AB-Tronic) actually drop around 300v on the skin, enhanced by conductive electrodes and gel, but the voltage is pulsed at a very low current.

Also, worth noting, the Alternating Current at home is NOT the kind of electricity that would make your muscles contract and make it hard to let go. It's an alternating voltage so muscles will contract one way then the other way, 50 times a second (or 60 in some countries). If you ever grabbed a live wire, you can actually feel the mains frequency.
It's DC (direct current) that's more dangerous as the muscles will contract and stay that way as long as there is current flowing.
